caption: Exceptional and fresh food, I loved the ambience the place has, and the employees were welcoming. Will definitely come back.
Calling it the best food in DC doesn't do it justice

I eat in this spot a lot since I work right next to it. I like how the service is always fantastic and they keep the spot well organized at all times. Pricing is fair and they serve sizeable portions.

We arrived at this restaurant for dinner. we heard about this restaurant from a lot of people.  Well, we were not disappointed. The crew welcomed us with a smile and we had an excellent feeling. The food was just great. We had a great time and we will definitely return to this restaurant. Warmly recommended.

I sent my friends to this place with my highest recommendations. I visit this place often. I get very good feedback from my friends. The the food there is yummy and the team is very friendly and cooperative. Every time  we go to this place we pass a lovely time.  I warmly recommend this restaurant.

I recently got Bad Saint for the first time for a birthday celebration. With the pick up and delivery options, it was a great opportunity to try their food without waiting in line. Obviously, the food was delicious. I had the stewed lamb which was phenomenal. What really blew me away was their care and attention to detail. When I emailed about ordering for a birthday, they asked for the person's name, and said they would include a card, which was extremely sweet! What was even more special was when I picked up the order, they also included a beautiful bouquet! It was a lovely meal, but the extra effort of including the card and the bouquet was what made it really memorable. Thank you Bad Saint!
Great little place with good food.
New chef but still has great Food!!
Would surely recommend eating here. Fantastic atmosphere, tasty dishes, great service. 5 stars.

I visit this place a lot since I work right next to it. I love how the customer service is always fantastic and they keep the spot well kept consistently. Prices are affordable and they serve generous portions.
One of my main spots to eat. fantastic location, neat, and good customer service. I highly recommend them!
Creative Filipino food in a cozy intimate space that feels like your go to place when you’re away from home and need some nourishing comfort.
Would certainly recommend trying out this place. Fantastic vibes, flavorful food, awesome service. Kudos.
They serve big portions and for reasonable rates. welcoming staff. 5 stars.
Bad Saint was fantastic. Everything was good but the green curry chicken and the red snapper really stood out. Since we are effectively trapped at home, this food provides a nice escape.
One of my main spots to eat. very good location, clean, and very good customer service. Very good job!
The food is constantly well prepared and yummy, staff members hands out fantastic customer service. I liked how clean it is and mood. Highly recommended.
Brought you stuff to try before you even order. Worth the wait, food lived up the the hype
I regularly stop by grabbing some food in this place. I enjoy the efficient customer service and well prepared dishes. Never disappointing.
Awesome ambience and very welcoming service. The menu was crisp and delicious. Will easily recommend this place to anyone. Affordable prices and generous portions. Good job.

last night was our first time we came to that fine restaurant. But It is obviously not the last time. We passed a splendid evening with the courteous service, with the excellent  food and wine and with the modest charge. We will absolutely return there again.
Simply the best Filipino restaurant in the city.

An increasingly well-known if miniature 24 seat D.C. gem in Columbia Heights, which now takes reservations. But you better call way ahead. The drinks and the food are a revelation. Filipino-inspired, you can order a la carte or be surprised with a chef's choice option. Either way, it's can't miss. Go there with a friend or partner and split 3-4 dishes, whether pork belly,  spicy noodles made on site, bitter melon, a delectable enchilada -- a terrific and cozy ride. The wait staff is convivial and professional and, given you're in a matchbox, unobtrusive.
Just spectacular food.

Greatest Flipino food in DC. Been there exactly  5 times. Including the time I didn't get in, pre-reservation era. The menu is inventive, no doubt about that. The ingredients are not conventional, yet they achieve the same baranguy flavor - how?! The chef clearly does his research and draws from experience. I have, however, came across exactly two dishes that were a bit too salty. I used to eat Kamayan out my palm, but what is cardio? Nonetheless the plates are balanced across texture, sweet, savory, and heart. Come through to the most innovative Filipino restaurant I've had the luxury to come across.
Great restaurant. The wait outside is no big deal and the food, service, and environment are great!
Amazing meal and hospitality
It took me long enough to get reservations at Bad Saint. Very happy with the food and the impressively unique recipes and dishes.
Very unique dishes

Not very impressed. Place is small and expect long wait. And I mean really small space, like eat at the counter, not many tables available. Don't think a good place for a date. Dishes are generally ok, salty, when things are salty they usually taste good. Honestly speaking I can not tell the difference that if I am eating Filipino dishes when I ate here. Not friendly pricing of course. Parking is street good luck to get any.
Fantastic food! Tiny space.

This restaurant is clearly one of the finest restaurants in the neighborhood. Always when I come to this place I am extremely satisfied. They always keep their high  standard service and the highest level of meals  they offer. You are always happy with this place. Highly  recommended.

This site is my preferable place.  Of all restaurants I know I like it most. I never miss an opportunity to go to this restaurant. Whenever  I I need a good lunchon, this is the place that comes immediately to my mind. extremely good and all kinds of  food and a rich cuisine.great crew, and nice ambience. In addition to that, the tariff is reasonable. I sent my friends to this place with great pleasure.

This site is my first choice site.  Of all restaurants I know I favor it most. I never miss an opportunity to go to that place. Whenever  I I need a superb dinner, this place comes immediately to my head. exeptionalgorgeous and all sorts of  food and a large menu.helpful staff members, and good vibes. Not less important, the charge is good. I tell about this place with pleasure.

I take my family to this great spot many times a year! This is the best place to have a bite.  I go to this spot frequently. The food is great, the staff is friendly and the payment is reasonable. I like being in this place over a tasty dinner.
One of the best dining experiences you will ever have.
Fantastic food. Very very small restaurant. Parties if two seem to sit in a bar like configuration against a wall. But the good makes up for it.

This place consistently shows why it is has earned its James Beard awards. Each dish is a culinary experience that you will remember until you are able to get your next reservation. The location itself is small and quaint but big on flavors. The only draw back for Bad Saints is getting reservations. The online process for getting reservations is painless, but you better be quick or else you will end up disappointed. But once you get your time in this small part of culinary heaven you will know that it was truly worth the wait.

We had to make a reservation a month in advance to get in the door. Service was impeccable, our server was efficient, pleasant and knew the menu well. The restaurant was pleasant, if a little compact. The food was excellent! The slow cooked pork was tender, luscious, richly smoky and benefited from the coconut (milk/water?) it was bathed in. The crisp pork skin was the best icing this cake could have! The crab curry was made from a rich, seafood broth, with plenty of crab meat. Though the flavor of the broth competed with the flavor of the crab a bit, would've loved a more crabby flavor. The bitter melon and egg salad might've been the star of the show! Layers of flavor and texture, with the fragrance of the flash fry in the wok always in the background. The hints of crunchy bitterness in each mouthful were perfectly balanced by the creamy egg and sauteed greens. Be generous with the lemon! Gave them four stars because the food was too expensive. But we were glad we ate there!
Would certainly recommend eating here. Great atmosphere, fresh dishes, awesome customer service. I recommend this place.
Tried this spot in the past with my friend and I am obsessed ever since. I enjoy the good character and delicious food and beverages. Fantastic work.

This place is my favorite site.  Of all restaurants I know I like it most. I always suggests to my friends to go to visit this restaurant. everytime  I want to go to a fair dinner, this restaurant comes straightaway to my head. excellent and diverse  food and a large menu.helpful crew, and great ambience. Not less important, the expence is modest. I recommend this restaurant with no hesitation.
Pricey but fun
Tasty food, friendly staff and great spot all around. Highly recommended!
This spot is worth giving a shot. They serve large portions for fair prices. Constantly well kept and with fantastic atmosphere. Will visit here again.
Delicious food but way overpriced

Incredibly disappointed on several levels. The service was bordering on neglectful, which is tough in a place that seats 20.... Did the tasting menu and sadly it went from good to barely passable. The amuse bouche was fantastic, however the lobster and pork were overcooked. There was a middle entree in which our party of two was served 1 salad, which at $95 per person feels outrageous, let alone when the drink pairing for the course is just a glass of vermouth.  Which brings me to the drink pairing... I can look past the boring wines (Ontario wine... In a tasting menu pairing???) But the gall to serve a 4oz pour of beer (non limited release maine beer co) or the same pour of cider is borderline criminal.  As someone who sought out, and competed for a seat at bad saint, I feel immensely disappointed In every aspect of my meal and service. I am grateful for the reminder that just because something is Internet popular doesn't mean it's good. I'd recommend you take your money and spend it at one of the many good establishments in the are, like the green zone bar, of  anything from Jose andres

My overall impression is that it's overpriced for what it is, though the portions are generous and 3 dishes were enough to make two people full. We ordered: tofu+grin vert+bok choy salad, sour ribs stew, clams+rockfish in coconut sauce (curry style). It was the first time that I had a curry that was salty instead of spicy, but I can't say that I loved it. We spent months on the waiting list before we got a reservation. In the end, given the price )($100+ for two people) and the large selection of great Asian restaurants in DC, it wasn't really worth the wait.
New to this area, wanted to get some good Filipino food.  Everything was pretty good, but environment could use some work, I waited forever and it was cramped inside.
Awesome food and great ambience

We got lucky with day-of reservations for dinner and really enjoyed ourselves! The restaurant space is very small - 40 seats tops - most of which are facing the window or wall. It's beautifully decorated and comfortable but certainly not for a large group. Onto the food:  Wow! It's very cool to see food from the Philippines elevated to this level. I'm a vegetarian but my partner isn't and we both found hearty, interesting dishes that we could enjoy. The portion sizes are actually bigger than I thought they would be and we took leftovers after getting 4 dishes between 2 people. The radish dish in coconut cream was amazing and so special and it's not to miss. The complimentary dessert was also a nice touch. I really enjoyed my cocktail too which had a coconut vodka-type spirit with some really interesting flavors, and the rye drink reminiscent of a Manhattan was also fantastic.  This is such a great spot for a special meal!
Delicious food. Very good at fusing different types of cooking influences but still having a Filipino taste to the dishes.
Loved it. Tiny place with delicious food. People were super nice.

Generally disappointing.  Here’s why the Chefs Tasting Menu we selected for our table of 4 disappointed: 1.  The portion sizes were too big and and we were not informed how the menu would progress and how to pace the meal.   The chef should control portions to ensure proper pacing. 2.  The dishes were delivered randomly versus working in succession to improve upon the palate. 3.  We were given 4 courses without a single fish or meat...yet there were 3 options on the menu.  We did not request vegetarian and were actually looking forward to the Branzino as the main course when abruptly they brought the dessert. 4.  The food was good but not great...it did not overwhelm the senses. 5.  The service was adequate at best.  No clear explaining of the dishes or the complexity of the ingredients or preparation. This experience was really disappointing based on expectations.

I finally ate here after hearing constant praise of the restaurant for weeks, only to find it completely over-hyped. Myself and a partner ordered the Chef's Tasting menu ($65 each for four shared courses + dessert) and after the meal we concluded that not a single item on the menu was near worth the price of entry. The meal consisted of radishes with a coconut paste dipping sauce, an egg-mushroom rice dish, an American-Chinese style vegetable stir fry,  pumpkin stew, and a cornbread cake. We did not finish even half of the main courses (not because the portions were too large, though!). I am writing my first ever restaurant review because of how disappointed I was with the food here. While nothing at Bad Saints was necessarily BAD, hardly any of the meal was enjoyable either. When the tab comes out to $100 per person, however, I expect a lot more than mediocrity especially given the sheer amount of good food options in DC. I'm giving it two stars instead of one because we unwittingly were there while they were experimenting with "local seasonal produce" which explained why we were served so much pumpkin and four vegetarian courses.

A nice vibe and a creative menu makes this tiny corner restaurant a pleasant place for dinner. If the price range would have been in a moderate range, it would have been a 4+ restaurant. Considering the price, however, ($65 per person for chef's choice dinner) the grade goes down to 3, as the food is good but clearly not something you should be asking $65 for. Nevertheless, could be worth a try if you're interested in trying Filipino cuisine (cannot vouch for authenticity) in a hip place - and willing to endure the 3 hour wait for getting seated.

Went here for our anniversary and the dining experience was nothing short of magical. Every dish is worth discussing. The space is tight but oh so bustling and charming. You could easily spend the whole night just watching the chefs shuffle through an open, tiny kitchen making working in such a small space look so natural and easy.
The best Filipino cuisine in the country! Will definitely return soon!

Amazing filipino inspired cuisine. Eating here brought beloved memories of family meals growing up, but with a bold and tasty twist. Delectable crab, lechon, octopus and short rib sinigang entrees and the best tofu dish I have ever had. Outstanding and friendly service. The wait is worth it!

Going to Bad Saint is like experiencing art with food. Both for the eyes and the palate. It’s definitely not like mom’s cooking and being filipino myself, it’s definitely not your typical filipino food. But the essence is there! I enjoy everything - every time! It’s also definitely a unique experience. It’s a restaurant of it’s own class. You cannot compare it to any other dining experience you have ever had in your life. Bad Saint is it’s own category. For every dish I’ve tasted - my mouth and my brain are having a great party! It’s so hard to explain. You have to go and experience it yourself!  I have eaten here 3 times since they have opened. Tried more times but the lines were tough to beat. Thank God for the new option to make reservations! It’s pricey - but like I said - it’s consumable artwork! Enjoy!

Best meal of 2019. Each item was better than the last. We had the yellowfin tuna with shrimp crisp and avocado, the braised pork with crispy skin, and the egg noodles with beech mushrooms. Every bite was amazing. They deserve every accolade.

Had been literally trying to get reservations fir a year so expectations were high for first visit and they did not disappoint. Great creative food, super friendly, knowledgeable and approachable service. Great experience, cannot wait to ho back, hopefully won’t take me another year for next reservations :)

Filipino food like my mom made it? No. Filipino food as she dreamt it. I've come back here several times since it opened. Each meal has not just been Filipino food "done well," but an adventure into flavors and smells beyond the standards like Adobo or pancit or lumpia I've gotten used to. Oh, and I took my mom there finally, and it has her seal of approval.
Definitely worth the visit. Food was cooked different from what i was expecting but in a good and interesting way. The lechon and crab was topnotch and will definitely come back to have those again.
One of my preferred places to eat. great location, always clean, and fantastic customer service. A must try!

I've traveled and eaten food in the Philippines so I was interested in trying bad saint. I read such great reviews but was very mixed about the dish's flavors.  What's good is that service was attentive. They also served a champorado bar which reminded me of real Filipino food. It had bits of crisped rice in it reminiscent of something they do at home to make use of leftover rice. It was served with a little chocolate sauce...and the chocolate was an acceptable quality.  Unfortunately not all the food really tasted Filipino to me.  Read on.  . The labanos was like a crudite. Crisp radish served with a cold smoked coconut cream and toasted pistachios. It was fun and tasty for a vegetable lover.  I only wish they would have made a hot dish (like chicken) with the smoked coconut cream since it's a Filipino dish not typically served in Filipino restaurants in the US.  The kinilaw ( ceviche) was alright. Very hot with all the bits of chili peppers.  A prettier version of what is usually served.  Now, what I didn't like were the pancit (noodles) and the piniritong isda(fried fish) we had. I was surprised because the pancit was well reviewed. In a nutshell, the flavors were not really Filipino.  The pancit was very very sweet. You would never find a sweet noodle dish in the Philippines except for Filipino spaghetti made with banana ketchup and hotdogs . But even this pancit was sweeter than Filipino spaghetti!  The deep fried branzino itself was ok...and eating a whole fish while trying not to choke on bits of fish spine and bone is so Filipino...like eating at someone's home.  But what I didn't like was it was served with a lot of this sauce that tasted like a brown colored vinaigrette with a LOT of knorr seasoning and salt! If you don't know what knorr seasoning is to a Filipino, it's like a bottle of their local Worcestershire sauce but it's made with soy protein and possibly monosodium glutamate. It was so strange ...not really a Filipino thing...to have that sour taste mixed with knorr seasoning.  I thought at first it was a take on Filipino escabeche (deep fried whole fish with sweet and sour sauce)  but this experiment  doesn't work. Please don't believe.that this is a Filipino dish.  We were hoping to be wowed but the main courses we had were a surprising letdown because they really weren't truly Filipino tasting.  Btw, there is no dessert menu fyi.
Delicious, friendly, cozy!
First time here and hand down The best Filipino food in the dmv area. 10/10
The food was really except for the egg noodle dish which was way too oily other than that I loved everything else.
Outstanding - loved everything, but the salad most of all!
Amazing food. This place is a hidden jewel in Washington DC
Had a great time. The crab dish and the raddish appetizer was sooo good.
I absolutely liked their dishes and service, awesome area nearby to my apartment. The employees are always very friendly. Will come back again.

If you enjoy standing in line for an hour and then being seated on a hard stool at a narrow counter-top cheek by jowl with other customers, all in order to drop upwards of $60 per person for kinda salty kinda sweet Asian fusion...then Bad Saint is the place for you!  The stir-fried egg noodles with mushrooms and vegetables ($30) was a particular disappointment: gloopy and sugary. Yeah, I could taste the bok choi, and the sesame oil (too much oil in fact), but none of the flavors really stood out the way I expect at a good restaurant. The jumbo crab was better ($40), rich and interesting flavors, but not to die for. Oh, and the complimentary dessert actually made me gag -- some kind of unsweetened chocolate brownie thing that was like eating a lump of lard. This feels like a place that is so hip that people are afraid to say it isn't as good as they had hoped. Nice people, good service, but still...
The customer service is regularly efficient, awesome ambience, super friendly staff. I will visit again when I get nearby.

I arrived solo and was able to immediately be seated. One of the line chefs greeted me and told me of his favored dishes. I went with a recommendation of his: a delicious seafood medoly including baby octopus, calamari, clams, prawns, and chinese sausage over fried rice and other herbs and spicy. They comp'd me a coconut dessert for no reason at all!  Wonderful staff, wonderful food. I highly rate it.
This place obviously knows how to treat their clients. Constantly with a super friendly attitude. The food is affordably priced, regularly flavorful and neat.
Awesome food, very friendly employees, consistently  awesome ambience. They charge reasonable pricing and the food quality is fantastic. Keep it up.
The customer service is always fast, fantastic atmosphere, super nice staff members. Will come back again when I am in town.
Excellence as always!!!

Wednesday Morning 11:00am. In order to secure a spot at Bad Saint,  you will need to be on their website reservation page at that time. If not, better luck next week. Hopefully you are lucky enough to lock down a table, because it is a very unique and pleasant dining experience. A cozy and unique setting places you at a small table or counter like seating area. Service is quick and offers a limited but creative menu. Every day contains a chef's choice as well, which takes you through a rotation of on and off menu dishes (we went with this). Each dish had something that made it both delicious and different from anything we have ever had(sauce, pepper, style of cooking etc). Everything is shareable plates, and doesn't require any extra seasonings or sauces that they do not provide. Excellent overall experience and worth putting a little extra effort into getting that reservation.

The food here was amazing, but be prepared to shell out some serious cash for a full meal (with a drink, tax, and tip it was about $100pp). The seafood is fantastic, as is the pig. The only way to get a spot is to reserve online Wednesday mornings @11:00am.
Was not able to be seated, but the buzz alone got me extremely excited to go back

Now that they take reservations we were finally able to get a table. We had a 6pm reservation and scored a great seat at the bar. Got to see the chefs cooking and had nice chats with the staff during our meal. Had two specials, a octopus salad and Ukoy. Both exceptional...full of flavor. Had a chicken entree. The 3 dishes were more than we could finish. Left, full, happy and can't wait to go again.

So very disappointed with the place and the food. There’s really nothing represents about any filipino cuisines in this place ...   a simple Lechon cost $40 dollars and taste totally nothing like lechon but more likely broiled pork, floating in disgusting taste onion sauce/soup or whatever you call it. 🙄 The place is so tiny that you need to squeeze your self in order to eat. The price is ridiculously so expensive. Rather recommend to go to  Texas De Brazil, pay $48, enjoy the large selections of buffet salads, seafood and eat all you can meats ... ☹️....  P.S One thing I learned though... anything that says Bad ...  means NOT GOOD...

Bad saint is worth the wait. The atmosphere was completely unpretentious. The service was superb. There was a non-alcoholic drink on the menu. And the hostess helped my husband find great gluten free options. We loved the food. It was creative, filling, and delicious.
The best Filipino food in the USA. They really understand how to elevate the classics
Crazy good. Lives up to the hype. Will go again.
Best meal in D.C. Loved the Ensaladang CastelFranco!  Loved the crispy rice pinipig on top!

My sister in law arrived yesterday and she just had to try the much acclaimed Filipino resto Bad Saint. Had to fall in line before 5.15pm and finally got in at 7:30 pm. Bad Saint did not disappoint. The presentation of the dishes was impressive. The staff was lovely and the Chef co-owner visited with us for several minutes. We enjoyed the creative dishes- ifugao, labanos salad, ceviche octopus, alimasag. Also had lechon but with a twist, more smoky. Cooked more like paksiw sans vinegar. 5 stars.
Lovely ...Lovely Spot!!!!!

Food was great, but fell just short of the hype and price. Crab was the highlight and should not be missed. The bitter melon cocktail was delicious, but the bitter melon salad was my least favorite dish.

This place is nice and cozy, and the food seems very well prepared, so I feel a little bad giving it a three-star review. Maybe I'd have enjoyed it a lot more if I ate seafood - it seems that's their specialty.  We had all four of the vegetarian dishes to share. Two of them were cold salads, and all but one were pretty bitter. The one I liked was very similar to an Indian chaat.  The restaurant is incredibly tiny, with a few tables and bar seating for everyone else. The servers need to be contortionists to get plates in front of people! I liked that actually, it reminded me of small restaurants in Asia. We were right by the door, and the hostess was turning prospective diners away left and right. I won't be going back any time soon, but if you like seafood or meat you'll probably enjoy it a lot more than I did.
Delicious food and wonderful presentation

After being twice, I don't get the hype.  Most disappointing is probably the lechon - which is more like (mediocre) pulled pork rather than roast pork.  The staff is fantastic (but it's the food that matters to me the most).
Great menu that's constantly changing and innovating.
First time here, and I have to say ,I will be returning soon. Their food is amazing, super yummy. I wish I knew about this place before. I totally recommend it .

We were finally able to secure a reservation (from someone's cancellation thank you!) after a couple years of conversations of coming to try Bad Saint. Would we come again? Under a different menu, yes totally. Was the dinner as stellar as all the hype? Not really, overhyped a tad, considering we weren't fond of 4 of the 7 dishes we ordered. We wanted to try everything since we were there, so we ordered almost every dish under the meat/seafood section! Verdict on the dishes: - Octopus & Purple Yams: this was the first dish that hit our table and we were so impressed with the burst of flavors. There was just the right amount of lime, coconut milk, spice - we all just wanted to drink the sauce! - Labanos (radish + burnt coconut cream and pistachios): this was so delicious, the cream and pistachios created such a wonderful sweet flavor which was cut into nicely with the radish flavor. - Rellenong Alimasag (crab): came with gluten sticks for dipping, this was both delicious and rich; had us wanting more! - Prawns with Tomato & Chile: the flowers here were so dainty! Prawns were grilled well, juicy and tender. The sauce had a very nice kick to it. - Off menu Eggplant + Tofu: dish tasted good, but was very "Chinese take-out tossed in the wok" flavors. Pricey too for what you get. - Chicken Dish: we ordered this as an extra because we were all still hungry and figured we would try everything. Dish came out with a soup and sate sauce. Soup was rich and flavorful, loved the bittermelon in it. The chicken was really just a Chinese-style ginger scallion "bai zhan ji". There weren't any creative takes on it - we could have had without this dish. - Lechon: we were extremely extremely excited about this dish to be disappointed. There must have been too much smoke in the dish or something, but the meat and skin especially, all tasted very chemical. The guys at my table ended up eating it all anyway since they were hungry, but I spit mine out unable to stomach the taste. Unfortunate. Service was great - our plates/utensils were replenished consistently and our server was knowledgeable on the menu. The restaurant gives you some chocolate covered bananas with your check to finish off the meal, but I would have loved to have a dessert. If there was a dessert menu we would have ordered everything to try it out. Please add some in the future!
Jus didnt like it

Great experience. Hard to get into but worth it. Food was awesome and the beverage side is both good and interesting. I also thought the atmosphere/layout was really cool (counter-style seating everywhere). Staff was really helpful and they know their stuff.

As soon as Bad Saint started a reservation system, I was in! Except I didn't read the instructions and kept logging in too late. Make sure to check on Wednesdays at 11am sharp! You will have no prob booking a spot.  My friend and I got the bitter melon dish, lechon, and lump crab in butter garlic. They were all delicious. The crab was amazing, lechon is a must, bitter melon was maybe an acquired taste. I wouldn't get that again but it was good. Three dishes was enough for us and it was topped off by a chocolate covered sliced of banana, a perfect bite of dessert.  It's worth it, but for someone like me, only once in a while or maybe only once. It's expensive. I'm more of a fast casual eater, so I would go back if a foodie friend came to town and wanted to try it. Otherwise I'll just go to Manila Oriental with my Mom.
A must stop if you have the options of planning WAY ahead of time.

Cant really judge Filipino food because I've never had it. All the dishes were tasty and well crafted.  A very small space for arestaurant.  cocktails were just good, not great. It is a 5 star restaurant but I think the hype left me hoping for a bit more.  Def worth a try though! Service was also great.
Arguably the best elevated  Filipino food being made today . Tom Cunanan needs to be recognized for this! Everyone is warm and wonderful and you will have a great experience!

When they say it's a small space, they aren't lying! Maybe 2 tables in the restaurant, everything else is counter/bar seating. The food was incredibly well executed and consistently cooked. We tried 4 items (2 people), and that was plenty of food. Portions are small, especially at the price point. The 4 star is based on the food feeling one note at times, and not like completely composed dishes. The crab was really good, but felt like it was missing a vegetal or herbal component. The pork was similar, although they included a few pickled veggies (but not enough). By the end of the meal, the Ifugao salad was the only outstanding dish we had. The rest were good, well executed, but felt incomplete. The bitter melon felt like it needed a hint of sweet to balance the more sour notes. Would return, but wouldn't have it on a priority list of places to visit.
Omg. Fabulous!!!!
Was worth the wait before, but now accepting reservations. A must-visit!

I've been to Bad Saint several times now and it never disappoints. The menu is updated frequently with seasonal options. Staff is incredibly knowledgeable and willing to answer questions about the menu and give recommendations. The owner is incredibly kind and passionate about food. Plus the cozy setting makes you feel like being there is a real treat. Absolutely lives up to the hype.
Lechon was delicious. Bitter melon went well with pork. We also got octopus ceviche - full of flavor!

By far the worst dining experience I have ever had in DC. Food took over 40 minutes to arrive. Had lechon which was pretty good but a little too much oil. Next had crab with butter and garlic which was inedible. Drenched in butter and oil and way too salty. Also served with over fried donuts???? Don't know who's idea that was. Last thing was fried squid, which was mostly fried rice dough. Barely any squid. Disgusting. Honestly shocked because this place had such good reviews. Will never return ever again.

Honestly disappointed. What we got for the price was kind of absurd. A pre fixed meal on NYE. The vibe is very intimate, and you have to wait in line to get a table (although supposedly they're toying with reservations now?). Probably won't go back, but was worth a try.
Super friendly staff, knowledgable, and I got a front row seat at the kitchen. Thank you chefs and front staff, you're doing wonderful work over on 11th! Must come back for more!!
Everything was delicious and they have great servers.

The food here is great! This restaurant is very small and the chances of you getting in without reservations is slim to none. The staff is cool and all very knowledgeable about the food and ingredients. The menu is very small but it changes pretty often. The ambience here is cool I really like how the bar and kitchen are set up.

The rice and asian pear salad was a light and refreshing start to a delicious meal. The veggie mix that came with rice was delicious.  The duck with crispy skin was the highlight of the meal and definitely stood above all the other dishes.  The squid puffs were very light and delicious, but the sauce was surprisingly fishy, which is something I wasn't used to.  The spaghetti was very well made, with a perfect handmade noodle.  The Filipino sweet rice dessert was semi-sweet and very filling end to a great meal.
Genuine and enhanced dishes that surprise and delight your tastebuds while comforting your soul. Super staff too. Unpretentious space adds to the charm. Well worth it! Unforgettable taste sensations.

We went a night where they were serving a set menu and it was very overpriced—especially because they served us pasta and meat sauce for the main course. Felt like we were being ripped off and only one or two dishes lived up to the hype.

I feel this restaurant is over-praised.  The food was good, not incredible, and it was pricey.  Service was slow and not very skilled, which was strange since there are only a few tables in the restaurant and plenty of staff.  The small tables are charming and cozy, but they're so tight that I was uncomfortable (I'm fairly tall) the whole evening.  I'd rather go to Purple Patch, the Filipino restaurant in Mount Pleasant, for good Filipino food and cocktails at a cheaper price in a more comfortable setting.  I think Bad Saint does have good, elevated cuisine, but I think it's over-hyped because of how small the restaurant is and how difficult it's been to get in.  I wouldn't go again.

Great restaurant. Long line when they opened but most people were making reservations for later so we were still able to get in and sat to eat right away. Is like high end Filipino food which should be an oxymoron but they figured it out. Some of it can be spicy and is not able to be adjusted that is only complaint. The chef was nice and talked a bit in tagalog!

To experience Bad Saint's Pagdiriwang celebration is truly a delight and heart warming experience, a prefixed menu curated for a delicious Filipino culinary adventure to kick off the new year and end the holiday season with a bang. We were fortunate to get a reservation for this extended event. Normally, one has to line up at 3:00 - 4:00 pm to get a seat at this cozy spot that seats about 24 guests. The menu included an assortment of dishes including black bass sinigang, a lobster rice tamale, lechon (of course), and Filipino spaghetti to name a few. With a rotating menu, we're always excited to see what Tom comes up with. He brings the comfort of home and his creativity and passion for cooking into each of his dishes with all the textures and flavors in every bite. If you are able to catch the window of opportunity to book a seat for one of their special events, do check it out. It was a nice perk to skip the line with all the snow, but even if you can't, Bad Saint is ALWAYS worth the wait!
Waited 2 years to get in.  Well worth the wait!
Very cozy, Philippine restaurant. It accommodates parties of 1-4 on limited to no reservations. Food and service are excellent and the wine and beer menu offer enough variety to explore.
Worth the wait in line...trust me!

Hands down best restaurant I've ever been to. The food impeccable, the service phenomenal, and the whole ambiance of the place was just amazing. The one place I actually enjoy waiting in line! They have a very unique system, l line starts forming at 3pm, business opens at 5pm, once you get to the front of the line you mention how many you have in your party and they tell you what time to come back. I wouldn't recommend parties larger than 4 due to the smaller size of the restaurant. Enjoy Bad Saint trust me you won't regret it!
Unique food, attentive service, nice ambiance. Great date night spot.

I don't understand why this place is so popular. First of all, the place is extremely small. It is so small, that it's actually really hard to make any movement inside the restaurant. The tables are ridiculously place, so there is no chance for you to socialize. I ordered an oxtail, and they literally put some beef spam on top of a naked bone, so I actually paid $35 for a can of spam! You are not going to feel like you are in the authentic Filipino restaurant. The music are westernized, no Filipino design at all, even the dishes (6 of those in total, used to be 7) don't taste unique.

Perhaps the best food I've ever had. Very cool and unique menu. The staff are amazing and kind, despite a long and busy night. They open at 5:30pm, and dont take reservations. You generally need to be in line by 5 PM for a reservation at some point in the evening, as they are very popular!
Really delicious and unique food. Well worth the wait for a table.

We were very disappointed to dine here and discover that the hype behind this authentic filipino restaurant was misplaced. I ordered a pancit dish and was served a dish with fettuccini noodles. I asked our server why the restaurant didn't use actual pancit noodles and was told that the chef preferred to serve a different type of noodle that was made in house. By taste alone I can tell you that the fettuccini noodles were barely distinguishable from store-bought. My boyfriend ordered a poke dish and was provided a very small bowl holding maybe 3oz of cubed tuna (and for sure, not a bit more). He was baffled by the small quantity (for the price) and the general lack of flavor.  Please note, all of these dishes are extremely pricy for what is offered, and did not stick out with genuine filipino flavors. Please don't waste your time and money here. Especially when there are so many amazing restaurants in the D.C. area.

I will come off as one of the few persons that wasn't pleased with Bad Saints.  Let's start with pros: - Nice and intimate little restaurant - Nice ambiance and great responsiveness over texts  Cons (worst on top): - Rude server - Very few options if you don't have a heavy spice resistance. The non spicy dishes are not impressive - Awful cocktails - Too pricy for what it is - Some plates are well elaborated, others are really poor - Very limited menu
Fantastic dinner! Totally worth the wait!

Not being familiar with the food actually added to the experience. The food was delicious,  the service excellent, a little pricey but well worth the experience.  Go get yourself some really good food.

Nothing bad about Bad Saint!  Get in line early.  Had to be 15 people in front of me and I arrived at 4:40...opens 5:30'ish.  Top of my list!  Trust the experienced staff with their guidance.  Relax and enjoy!
Excellent food and service. We went fairly late, so we did not have to wait in line to be seated, which was great!
(Translated by Google) om name  (Original) om nom

My favorite restaurant in DC. If you have the opportunity to eat here, take it. Very few seats so be prepared to wait. I recommend getting a drink at Wonderland or El Chucho while you wait for your table. The menu is always changing but believe me when I say it is some of the most unique and delicious dishes you'll ever taste. I didn't think it was possible to elevate Filipino food to a level of elegance, but this is exactly that. If you enjoy your meal at Bad Saint, I recommend trying to find a Mom and Pop Filipono run restaurant such as Lumigs and taste the dishes you tried in their original forms. It definitely won't be as decadent as Bad Saint, but you can see how the dishes taste in their indigenous form. I love homecooked Filipino food, but this restaurant really does enrich these dishes without taking away from their original charms and essences. If you don't take this opportunity to try this amazing restaurant, you're really doing yourself a disservice.

This place will knock your socks off!  You have to get in line early to get a table as seating, most of which is bar stool chairs, is at a premium.  Their coconut radish dish was mouth watering, which is saying something since I hate radishes.  And the pork was amazing.  No knife needed as the meat fell right off the bone.  This Filipino food newbie was definitely be back.
I loved it. Everything was great. Wonderful presentation, perfect balance of flavors and spices.

I am at work right now. The staff here is SUPER nice and more accommodating than my expectations. The woman at the door is very personal (and super hot). I am normally a carnivore but the dish suggested to me.....OMG! It is AMAZING!!!! It is a vegan dish. I'm coming back!!!!
Better than Filipino food in the Philippines (Cebu, Boracay, Dumaguete, Bacolod). No joke. Trust me.
This is the best Filipino restaurant ever
Fresh food

I love Bad Saint. I had one of the best meals here. It’s a unique Filipino restaurant. There are so many options and everything is delicious. The place doesn’t take any online reservations so you have to wait in line (which is usually long) to be seated. We waited for a couple of hours and it was worth the wait. I cannot say enough good things about this restaurant. The food was delicious, the service was great and the it’s budget friendly. All around it’s a win.
Outstanding food with a wide variety of taste. Chef has a real understanding of the use of spices
Unrelenting and unapologetic take on Filipino food. Definitely worth the hype. Try one of the line waiting services if you don’t want to do the waiting yourself, either way, it’s worth it.

Excellent food and service - have had some things I've never tried before. The bitter melon was excellent. The only down side is that the restaurant is TINY (probably only 10-14 tables) which causes absurd waits. They do two seatings per night;  expect to have to stand in line early to get a table - I got there two hours before they opened....

300% worth the wait and the hype. The flavors and the attention to detail made for a delectable and luscious, yet homey experience. Typically with DC restaurants (even the top ones), I find that it's difficult for many restaurants to provide as much attention to detail and *character * to each and every dish because of just how massive DC restaurants tend to be, but my friends and I were definitely pleasantly surprised with Bad Saint. We also loved the charm, the atmosphere, the aesthetic, and the incredibly well-spoken and well-informed staff. We felt like we were in a hole-in-the-wall restaurant in Brooklyn or LES
Radishes, and the tuna are amazing. The cocktail I had was great too, it was the less sweet option they had. Wish the music playing matched the bathroom tho!
Incredible food, service, and overall experience. One of the city's best for sure

Unique small plates, cooked authentically. However, out of 4 plates we ordered, 3 were too salty. I cant take too much rice due to diabetes nor too much salt due to hypertension. If you take the food allergy into consideration so well, please also consider other health factors such as sodium and carbs. A bit disappointed. Not worth the price.
As always very well crafted menu and rich flavors. Quaint little place with great vibe...something about the comfort in that place. Even something as simple as radish was so good and well plated.

My party of two got in line at 4:45 on a hot Saturday and got in for the first seating, much to our surprise. I'd rather just make a reservation, but the food was good enough that I'd definitely go back, line and all. We split the asparagus with brown butter, the prawns with black garlic, and the beef rendang. While we were open to ordering more, that ended up being enough for us. The rendang was both of our favorite - super flavorful and perfectly cooked - but everything was lovely. We were also impressed with the beer offerings. There weren't tons of options, but what they had was delicious and offbeat. Our waiter was slightly quirky but extremely pleasant, and the service was prompt and well-paced.  I've seen at least one review complaining about the seating, which is mostly bar stools facing mirrors. It's a little awkward! But we just laughed about it and mostly looked at the food, and it wasn't a big deal. That said, if you can't sit comfortably on a bar stool, you might want to call ahead to see if they can accommodate you.
This was, hands down, one of the best dining experiences I've ever had. Food was very expensive, worth every penny.
If someone else waited on line I would go all the time. The line was pretty brutal though
Premiere Filipino fusion restaurant in Washington DC... Only drawback is small and YOU MUST get there early to line up... NO RESERVATIONS! So if not early enough, check Purple Patch as a backup...
Best food ever eaten.
Amazing food and service, well worth the wait!
Amazing food and drinks! I wish they would allow reservations however (even for only a few tables), as you have to stand outside for quite long before opening to get a seat.

Worth the wait. Enjoyed everything I tried. Definitely a spice heavy menu, but there were a few options if you didn't like too much spice. Extremely considerate when it came to food allergies. Also, despite the long wait, their notification system via text makes it super easy
One of the best meals of my life. The food was beyond what I was expecting, complex and amazing. The service was second to none.

I arrived to the restaurant at 3:30 p.m. on a Monday and discovered and I was the first in getting there. The line didn’t really start intensifying until an hour later.  During the two-hour wait I made a friend in line while we each waited for a friend. We ended up eating together in a table of 4, which is the largest Bad Saint offers.  I highly recommend arriving early and getting a larger table to be able to try more dishes. We had 6 dishes among us, and paid $40 each plus tip. Dishes are large enough that you wouldn’t want to be eating them solo.  For a place with such an elegantly short menu, waiters were super accommodating with dietary restrictions and allergies: they helped us with the selections and offered to put items on the side. The staff, all together, are some of the nicest and most helpful people you will meet!  The wait was definitely worth it. I experienced the most pleasant two hours with new friends over lots of flavourful unique dishes — every single of which I enjoyed. My favorite one was the Bitter Melon stir-fry. Not everyone at the table loved it but if you like bitter and unique bites, I would recommend it. Bad Saint is particularly amazing at making the best sauces to accompany each dish.  Photo credits go to my friend Lee.
Tremendous food and great vibe

I normally disregard random poor reviews on places such as this, as “oh they are just picky”, etc. But, I stand corrected, they are in fact correct. Not only is the restaurant extremely stuffy and excessively warm (we ate on a 98 degree day) but the seating is about as uncomfortable as it comes. Unless you have 3 or 4 you are obliged to sit on a bar stool and stare at your self in a mirror for your entire meal. That aside, I was expecting to override all of that with some splendid food as been hyped for quite some time but was sadly let down on that as much as possible. Out of 5 overpriced dishes the only one that was redeemable was the white asparagus.  There’s very little on the menu that provides a relative description of what your about to it. The lobster dish was just ok, very much like an Indian green curry stew, the soft shell crab was boring, the bitter melon really had nothing to do with melon and was mostly over salted stir fry and the largest disappointment of the evening was the chicken in a pot. More or less it was boiled chicken, skin on which was tough and completely flavorless. Pretty saddened about the entire experience. Save your line waiting!
Possibly the nicest staff you’ll ever meet. They were so attentive and friendly, made the experience feel homey. Food was unique and amazing. The cocktails were excellent too.
Food was amazing. Filipino food to the next level. Just wish they had more things on their menu and that the prices were more reasonable

The food was good. Place seems pricey for what we got but it's a hot spot. Also the lack of reservations always hinders me from giving places like this 5 stars. Good for a one time try but I would not go back unless I had people come in from out of town.

Filipino food with a twist! Ate adobong sugpo (prawns) and piaparan na manok (chicken) and both was awesome. I only gave it 4 stars  because it was pricey and the portions was small. Paid 70+ for the two dishes (without drinks). You also have the to wait 45 mins to get a table.

It's impossible to get a table here but it's for good reason because this place is amazing. Beautiful ingredients, great staff and cozy environment. Seating is quite tight inside but it's so worth it.
For the unaware, you're sitting on an uncomfortable stool in a hot restaurant paying for overpriced, low rate fare. Also, the staff is super snooty. So be prepared to be inundated by judgey glances.

Bad Saint offers a very innovative dining experience: The dishes are truly unique and delicious. The fettuccine with crab fat and fermented red peppers is definitely one of the best dishes I've had in my life. The service complements the dining experience very well. The waiters are incredibly friendly and they guide the guests through the menu with good knowledge of the food that they offer.

Uninspiring.  We some how managed to get a seat on a Saturday night with little to no wait. The atmosphere was reminiscent of a small neighborhood eatery with a friendly and knowledgable waitstaff. The food was bland and left us wondering how such mediocre dishes created the cult like following of this Columbia Heights eatery. The prawns were undercooked with a heavy soy sauce flavor, the squid ink unnecessary. The kale and lobster dish tasted like a fishy crawfish étouffée with too much celery, the pork belly an unmemorable salty mush. The closest thing to a highlight was the French morning radish with coconut and pistachio purée. The bottom line was uninspired Filipino comfort food that left us confused as to how such an average restaurant had garnered such attention.

The best Filipino restaurant in the District and one of the best restaurant in the whole DC-Maryland-Virginia area. The dishes are wonderfully crafted with complex but always delightful tastes. The service is excellent and always willing to give recommendations. I personally recommend ordering three dishes for two people.

The staff was VERY friendly and helpful.  I grabbed a seat at the bar and basically let the servers make my decisions for me.  I had the pork belly with some type of blood sauce - was delish.  I also ordered a couple of cocktails that were a perfect pair to the dish.  This place definitely lives up to the hype but you better get there right when it opens!
Awesome spot. Great food and great service. Small, personal spot. Be prepared for long waits. Does not take reservations and takes only parties 4 or less.

Absolutely fantastic! They don't take reservations (at least at the time that I went). So be warned that you'll  have to wait outside for a few hours before they opened. But it was worth every minute.
So awesome!
Amazing. Worth waiting (and if you PLEASE go to the wonderland ballroom next door). Perfect service, outstanding food, lovely location.
EXCELLENT FOOD!
Amazing! Very interesting flavor combos, every foodies dream.
Worth the wait in line, for sure! Such an amazing and flavorful meal. From the radish and burnt coconut salad to the prawn dish pictured below, everything was fantastic!

Unreal food. So flavorful and delicious. Nothing like I've ever tasted before. A bit pricey. We got in line at 4pm on monday and were #6 in line for the first round of seating. So worth the wait. Stellar meal.
Absolutely worth the line up and wait. The dishes were great examples of filipino cuisine with delightfully unexpected twisted. A ,must try.
Quaint ambiance & Special gastronomic excursion in the heart of Columbia Heights.
Worth the wait! Great vegetarian options. Great cocktails, though the menu was very short. Service was great.

My experience here was fantastic! The staff was so wonderful and gracious. The food was absolutely superb. It was the perfect blend of spicy and smooth. I visited with a group of 4. Although the wait is long it's totally worth it. Genevieve (our hostess) was fabulous. She was so warm and inviting. I loved talking with her and learning about the restaurant. Great job! We will always recommend.

We continue to be VERY impressed with these young FilipinaFilipino resto-preneurs! Cannot wait for their "Phase 2"... hopeful hopeful... Salamat e grazie mille  ;-)  From our most recent visit:  our top fave was the pancit "Nero" (pancit sontanghon).  Close second was the sisig, veggie version (shrooms instead of pork bits) which worked really well! The dinuguan, traditional version, brought me back to childhood's "chocolate meat" (haha).  LOVE how the menu changes and evolves constantly, blending tradition with innovation!

Tip: Make friends (or friendly conversations) with the other people waiting in line for 1-1.5hrs. Intimate restaurant. Fun lighting. Unique flavor combinations. Very attentive staff who check in and fill water without you needing to ask. Owner is very hands-on and buttons up details. Accommodating to people with allergies. Great place to celebrate birthday. The richest options of each menu section were a little too rich for my taste towards the end of the meal. Great experience.

Good stuff. My wife and I celebrated a late anniversary here, shared 3 dishes and drank water, the bill was just under 100 bucks. Snapper was fresh and we'll cooked, presentation was terrific. My favorite dish was the califlower and kobacha squash dish. I would definitely go back and try the pork belly which they had run out by the time our reservation had come, after 10pm. I don't think I would frequently come here if I lived here, but would enjoy on special occasions.
Very good food, wish they'd stop with the dumb system of no reservations. Their system makes it arbitrary luck if you can get a table at a reasonable time.

As a Filipino, I love that this place is repping and showcasing our food in amazing and new ways. Super inventive and hip. Awesome space. Great cocktail and beer selection. Food was delicious too. My only issue was our table of four wanting to order everything on the menu and being told by the server that we might have too much food because the dishes aren't "small plates". Super refreshing to hear except that our first clam dish came out with 8 little neck clams or 2 clams per person. And a dumpling special with one dumpling per person. All of this would have been fine if the expectation for "not small plates" hadn't been set early on. I would totally recommend eating here, just know that plates are small and you shouldn't be dissuaded from ordering everything!

The quality and flavor of the food was great (5 stars). The portions are on the smaller side.  The overall value is lacking as the dishes are way over priced (2 stars).  The ambiance is horrible. Very small dining area and they cram people in like sardines (2 stars).  Service - the wait staff is great. The hostess was very rude.  Bad Saint does not take reservations. You’ll need to show up 30-45 minutes before they open to get a table.  In summary, this place is not worth the hype. The overall experience and value are lacking. Plenty of better options in the city.
Good food but a bit off with the hostess

Definitely good food but nothing extraordinary: the pork belly was good (but I've had much better, e.g. at Sushi Taro), the beef stew was just ok (my wife's is much better!), and I didn't like the mushroom medley. Wine-wise, the viognier was ok but not more at $17, and the 2 reds by the glass were good (SP & PT). Service was friendly and great (albeit a bit slow), but it doesn't warrant the long no-reservation wait, and being crowded at a bar in a very noisy environment. The menu is also very limited, basically 8 dishes in total (appetizers + mains).

Oddly enough as I write these words about Bad Saint, I am sitting in a beach resort in Laiya-Aplaya. The food that I enjoyed is fantastic! Bad Saint is the real deal people. The ribs, prawns and bitter Mellon were on point. If you want a great representation of what you will get in Manila check them out. Right now I am getting ready for a wedding between my good friend and his Filipina fiancee.  Cheers!!

Was looking for unique restaurants in DC for a weekend trip and of course found Bad Saint. Sadly, i feel that the food itself is very hyped up for very little reason. Had no choice but to order a 7-course set menu due to the holiday season. Other than the first course and a fettuccini (pictured below), all other courses tasted not far from regular Asian home cooking. For that, this meal was way too expensive. Also had a suspicion that they swapped beef tongue for beef chuck or shoulder in the stew... Maybe we came at a bad time?

Hard to get vegetarian Filipino food, especially good vegetarian food. This place has it. The no reservation policy is a drawback, but if you go on an off day and show up 15minutes before opening you should get a table.
Wonderful and unique food served in a small space. It is worth standing in line for.

The management team needs to find a better way to get people out of the cold during the winter.  It was ridiculous that the staff was letting people in one table at a time.  AFTER waiting 2 hours in the cold, many people still had to wait an additional 30 minutes to be put on the waitlist. The staff were generally friendly,  though some were haughty in their explanation of the meal.  The omnivore holiday menu was also uneven at best, with a delicious beef tongue dish and mushroom stir fry and mediocre scallop and salad dish.  The dessert was bland.  The vegetarian menu was slightly better but still uneven and is the only reason I didn't rate my meal lower.  To whom much is given, much is expected.  Having given 2.5 hours of my time in line and 200 plus bucks of my money,  the experience was well below my expectations.  Maybe with the regular menu during the spring or summer will be better.  I hold out hope.

Don't let the hype taint what is a good meal! Well put together menu with some seasonal changes. Too small, annoyingly so. The lines and wait are ridiculous. But if you've got time to hang at one of the other neighborhood spots (try El Chucho!) and aren't starving when you put your name in, you'll have a good time.
Great tasting menu
This place is suck because my friend Homer is pinoy
Food was flavorful, similar to homemade Filipino food. However, overall meal seemed overpriced.
Food was good but such a small venue

Yes. Amazing. Go. Arrive 1-1.5 hours early to put your name down for one of their 3 seating time options. The staff is great and are very hospitable. They make sure you have a great experience beginning to end. Note that their menu changes often, so there could be something you've hear of that may be not be there when you go.
Definitely worth the wait!

Dined with my family and we are hard to please foodies.  I eat filipino food often because my buddies at work are forever taking the scraps and make something amazing.  Bad Saint did not fail to please. The flavors were familiar and innovative,  and the atmosphere was great.  Small,  quaint,  and full of dancing flavors for  on your pallet.
The best Filipino food I have had in DC area so far.
Yummy and delicious with personal service

Staff were all WONDERFUL.  The food did not impress me.  We had the tuna, bitter melon, and a squid special.  The squid was really lovely,  but the tuna was basic and the bitter melon did not impress.
Fantastic time with Filipino food. Not just a lumpia and pancit stand. Expect a primer on the flavors of different areas of the Philippines.
WOW. ABSOLUTELY STUNNING!!

Didn't live up to the outlandish hype. Some parts of the meal we're really delicious (the swordfish curry was sublime), but overall an inconsistent experience. Service was great (including adding extra portions to an entree to match the number of people in our party), but I felt that asking us to leave just a few (like 5 or 10) minutes after the check was paid was rude and beneath a restaurant that has the reputation that this one does. Cocktails we're fantastic, but some of the appetizers (the bland rice salad) were substandard. All in all a mixed bag. In my opinion some elements were promising, but overall not worth the wait, not worth the hype, not worth the price.
Excellent meal!   Definitely worth the wait.
Awesome food, service, and overall experience. There is usually a line to get a table, but we got lucky because it's Game of Thrones night :)
I hated waiting in line, but the food was amazing and the owner is the real McCoy. She is cooking her mothers recipes with passion and it shows. Just go.
Great Filipino food

I can't say enough how great this place is! The staff was kind enough to let us come right at closing since it was me and my wife's anniversary. The food itself was truly worth the wait times to get places on their list. If you to DC Bad Saint is a must.
Pricey and small portions. Very good food. Could be a loooong wait. Glad we tried it.
Well worth the wait.
Food was not very good. Surprised this was on Washingtonian 's list at all, let alone top ten.
Overated and salty Filipino food.  Owner is salty too...
Weird wait policy

I had the pleasure of dining at Bad Saint last night and want to tell you that the food and staff are outstanding!  I have one suggestion that would really make your customers A LOT happier – improve your seating/hostessing technique.  After waiting in line for hours for the restaurant to open, the last thing you want to do is wait another 45 minutes to talk to the hostess once the doors open at 5:30.  The hostess took a full 4 minutes to seat the first party in line, in a completely empty restaurant, that only has 28 seats and it was only two people.  Can’t quite figure that one out!  Perhaps if you had more than one person acting as host it would be better.  Maybe one host seating people who are ready and another putting the names on the waitlist.  It would really make the line standing less horrible and make for happier customers.  Glad I did it once because the food was delicious, but eating out is about more than the food.  I’ll be back when you take better care of your clients.
Yum yum yum. Fantastic food bursting with complex and interesting flavors. Delicious cocktails. Get here early otherwise you may miss out on a table at all. Extremely good service. Love this place.

Plan your evening to get there a couple of hours before they open and expect to wait in line. If available, sit at one the tables facing the open kitchen. The food is unique so take your time selecting your dishes. The food is great and there's no dessert but your bill will come with a sweet big enough to share.
Very good quality, but limited options.
Mediocre. For the hype I expected more.
Worth it.
Can't be beat, just show up early for the line!
Everything was great but didn't quiet live up to the hype in my head. Still, highly recommend.
Too small a place....
The best seat in the house is to be had at the counter facing the kitchen. The staff are great and the food is superb with the right balance of flavours from the sadly overlooked Filipino cuisine.
Simply amazing. Fresh flavor coming 9it of the kitchen does not stop! Fantastic meal, fantastic hospitality, thank you so much!
Delicious Filipino cuisine

The atmosphere is nice, yet a bit cramped. The food was overall OK. Our server recommended one dish that was unpalatable (bitter melon with black beans and fried egg). It was a nice experience, but the food didn't blow my mind in a way that would make me come back anytime soon.
Worth the wait!
The Chef is a culinary genius!  Everything harmonizes together into a truly unique experience!

Service and food is absolutely wonderful. The menu changes every so often, featuring different new dishes. It's worth the wait in line. The atmosphere is charming: every small detail from the upholstry to the ceiling art has it's history and story.

"Filipino food, Flavors that is worth the wait."  I never really knew what the hype was all about, I had read about the place online, seen pictures of the food, but I had never had the chance to try it. Until now.  We wanted to celebrate my fiance's birthday weekend here. Planned out to come to the place and wait it out for some time. Interestingly we actually met someone waiting in line that had been coming back to this place multiple times, willing to wait just to get a bite of this authentic Filipino cuisine.  The time came up and we got in, Wow, not what I expected for all this hype, not at all. Place has very limited seating.  Host got us to our table and introduced the menu. Of course as we usually go on these food trips we love to indulge on the best they have to offer. So we did.  At the end of this all, we were at awe, the various flavors that they offer from variety of dishes are worth the wait. Seriously, it is.  For all the food lovers out there, if you want to cross that off your list of authentic food flavors, swing by and savor it. Hope this helps!  Karl Cabadin @kcSnapimagery
Italian, but not your typical. Authentic, different and tasty. Excellent Italian wine selection. Will need reservations, stays busy!
Great food and drink

Great atmosphere, there are only 20 seats and they are very cozy so conversation is encouraged. The food is very unique, small menu of unique, delicious dishes to choose from. If you want to get a table when they open at 5:30, you'll have to be in line by 4:30 at the latest.

food was really good and so was the service but they need to find another way to place reservations. I stood out in below freezing weather for 50 mins so I can get the reservation for me and my sister.
Totally worth waiting in line. Been twice and it was two of the best meals I've ever had.
Worth the wait.  Seriously.
Great food for the adventurous!
This place deserves the hype.  Ambiance is great, food is fantastic.

We had dined here many  times before but each experience is exiciting, phenomenal flavors and consistent personal level service as always! We thoughted the Octopus Ceviche.  being the day after Christmas, the lines would be shorter...but no...there are even more people eager to try this restaurant. The line started at 2:30pm for a first seating experience. If you manage the your expectation, and patiently wait...it is so worth the wait and the hype. I laugh at the comments who write not about what is inside...rather than the line. We ordered the Octopus Ceviche, Ampalaya (Bitter Melon Gourd) sautéed in egg with black fermented beans, Grilled Bronzino with "Maggi", Lime and Vinegar sauce, Kale and Taro leaves sautéed in Coconut Milk (Laing), the Clams sautéed with Chinese Sausage and Chinese Donut crullers, and Pancit Molo sautéed with crispy garlic and shallots, onions and stuff. Dessert was a collection of miniature apple fritters wrapped in egg roll wrappers with cinnamon. What a treat! What a menu! Chef Tom Cunanan, please bring back your Signature Ukoy. But the menu, service, experiencewas beyond our expectations. Diner must order the amount equivalent to the number of people in the group...at least or more. We are already planning our return! For the naysayers that complain, please just go somewhere else and stop taking valuable space! Better for the fans! I cannot wait for the next menu!
Delicious food! The space is small and there's a long wait to get seated.

I can't say enough great things about this place. Yes you have to show up early to get a table and yes it's a small joint with limited seating, but it is all worth it.  I had the pleasure of visiting here while Tom Cunanan was in the kitchen and he didn't disappoint. We ordered 3 dishes (plenty of food for 2) and each one was unique and delicious. My favorite was the arroz Caldo, followed closely by the tocino dish. What surprised me most was, despite putting a fancy spin on these very traditional Filipino dishes, a lot of the flavors reminded me so much of my dad's cooking. The quality of the meal is much higher, but the underlying taste still reminded me of home, which is something I hadn't experienced at any other Filipino restaurant.  Now the real test is going to be the lumpia dish, so I hope he's serving that next time I go!
Incredible
Good service, most of the food was good. It's a very interesting and unique experience that can be appreciated. I think it's a little over hyped.
Okay but over rated. Ordered 3 items, one was good, another too salty and the third was just too many flavors or twicking done did not taste anything like what it was suppose to be.

This tiny restraint packs some big flavor and a great waitstaff. Just be prepared to wait in line before opening to get a seat. Take the opportunity to socialize with your fellow line-waiters. It all makes for a uniquely lovely evening!

The food is delicious! The atmosphere was fun and authentic to it's decor. The co-owner Genevieve was a great hostess😘👍 I will definitely be coming back inspite of long waiting..standing in line it was all worth it. A must try if you are in Metro DC.. Make sure to wear comfy shoes for walking.
The wait is long, and the food's taste isn't that amazing. They use alot of different ingredients which you think should be really tasty product, but just everything I tasted was just mediocre.

If you have not eaten here yet, WHY NOT? I first visited Bad Saint in April 2016, when I was in DC for a conference, and discovered the amazing food, drinks and people of this treasure. The dishes ranges from petite to enormous, with a fantastic array of flavors & textures, and drinks to match, in a handsome setting (but not spacious: best for 1 to 4 people). I have a more-than-passing familiarity with Filipino food, and these chefs are inventive, restless, and really exciting. Don't expect the same menu the next time you come back; it will be different. If an item looks like you cannot pass it up (& there will be several), eat it right now! Aside from being skillful & stylish, the staff at Bad Saint is incredibly warm. I came back after 4+ months and all of them remembered me. That may be because I sat at the solo seat at the counter, facing into the kitchen: a ringside seat for taking your tastebuds to the circus. Things I have had here range from a rich lemongrass goat curry, to fantastic kinilaws (one involved mackerel, pomelo, radishes & coconut cream; another was tiger prawns, papaya & cucumber with chilis & lime), to a ginisang with bitter melon, scrambled egg, fermented black beans & tomato, and a super-crispy ukoy the size of the crown of England. The line outside Bad Saint may be long for a while now, since Bon Appetit just dubbed them the 2d best new restaurant in America, but if you want to skip the line, go solo & sit at the counter. Tell them I sent you.
If you can get in, do it. Extremely worth your time.

The Bad Saint crew, from the door, to the wok, to the bar was in sync, spicy, crunchy and sweet in a way that will make you stop mid-bite and call your friends.  It is now one of 3 places I will recommend without reservation to friends, clients, and anyone else who needs a special bite and drink in their mouth. Don't miss!

What a crazy process to get into this place. People start lining up an hour in advance of opening time just to score a seat in this place, and man was my anti-hype radar on high alert, but when you get in you realize that the food here is pretty legit. Nothing like it in...possibly...all of the US? Really interesting, deep, complex flavors and ingredients...well...maybe interesting to someone who's not Filipino (myself), but it's a welcome member to the growing Asian palate in America.
Delicious!! It is a small place though so get there early (between 4 45 and 5 15) to get in line.  Totally with it!

This restaurant do not have a business phone number. To make reservations, you have to physically do it face-to-face. The average wait is 2+ hours and this restaurant will change/cancel your reservation at their convenience.

One of my favorite meals in the city. They don't take reservations, so you have to put you name on a list, and wait, or show up 20 minutes before they open and get in on the first sitting. Me and my wife go with our infant daughter and they are super accommodating. the food and the atmosphere are both exceptional.
Very overhyped. The staff was all very friendly and great but the food was a rip off.

I went because of Tom Sietsema's rave review in the Post.  it was ok, but overall a disappointment.  First: the wait.  They don't take reservations so we spent 45 minutes standing in line before they opened.  We were just short of first seating and told it would be an additional hour 45 minutes for a table.  After waiting that out at a bar nearby we found the table very crowded, with the guy behind me and I apologizing for knocking into each other many times each.  The ladies I was with were told that they couldn't come in with the few sunflower seeds they had in their hands because "no outside food or drink is allowed".  I decided to zero out the tip at that point, though I later relented.  From there it was just a pretentious take on Filipino classics.  Everything was tasty, though the chef seems overly fond of ginger.  The three Filipinas I was with were all unimpressed.
I always leave feeling well cared for and on a food high.

The food was delicious and very much worth the wait. Since they don't take reservations and the location is very small, we had to wait quite a while for a table, but they gave us a time slot and texted us when a table was ready. The seating inside is quite cozy and the decor eclectic. The staff was incredibly accommodating, asking several times if either of us had any food allergies or things we prefer not to eat and tending to us quickly. Overall, I would DEFINITELY go there again.

Whoa. In from out of town and decided to stop in. I just had by far the best chicken dish. Everything ordered was incredible. The bursting flavors in each dish are a lot to comprehend. It's bold, it's very worth it, and the service did an excellent job of explaining and introducing the menu items for someone not super familiar with the dishes. Try this sppt.
Amazing Filipino food in a small but great space. Definitely worth the 1hr+ wait. Get on the list, grab a drink at one of the nearby bars and come back when they call you.
Such a treasure. Small place so hard to get in but with the effort.
Authentic food and great service. Worth waiting there for an hour before it opens at 5:30pm.

For those complaining about small portions, it seems like they were listening and now the portions are more than generous. We were three [very hungry] adults and two kids, and we barely managed to finish our 5 shared plates. The menu is small but everything was delicious and fresh, and there are a good number of vegetarian options. Service was wonderful and the staff are very accommodating. I wasn't blown away by the cocktails considering their price but that's not why you come here.
Amazing food. Different flavors. Good Vibes. Friendly Staff. Punk rock bathroom.

Delicious Filipino comfort food in a casual, intimate atmosphere. The dishes were all phenomenal, and the service was outstanding. Kai was one of the best servers I've had in DC, and Geniveve was extremely helpful as a host. Highly recommend!

As we are used with Room 11, Bad Saint doesn't disappoint. The wait was long but well worth it. The food was delicious, and wish we had more room in our belly to try the entire menu. However, the recommendations were fantastic -- even if they had just changed the menu and we weren't able to try the pork belly. The cocktails were perfectly made. The staff were super friendly.
One of the best meals I've ever had. Chef Tom kills it.
This place is about the experience of consuming fantastic food. It is a must.

Great Restaurant, but very expensive. We went to Bad Saint for a school project, and this was one of the locations we visited. We tried a variety of their dishes, but the food portions were very small with a very large price tag. But other than that the restaurant itself was awesome. Very small, but the atmosphere was very cool. The food was delicious, and the drinks were wonderful. We had a great time :)

Five stars all around. My Monday night dinner buddy and I went here for a Monday night dinner and LOVED it. The restaurant is right next to Room 11 in a small space that fits around 26 or so. It's small and most of the tables are along walls, but it works without making you feel crowded. The restaurant itself looks like a top NYC restaurant.  The food and drinks are out of this world! We ordered the mango salad, pork belly, shrimp fritters, and beef/pork spring rolls. Each dish came out perfectly presented, full of flavor, and amazing. There wasn't a thing we didn't like. Also, get the one dessert they have. I LOVE chocolate and have a bad attitude toward non-chocolate dessert, but this dessert rivals even Swiss chocolate. It's purple rice, coconut milk, plums, and peaches, which sounds disgusting, but it's OUT OF THIS WORLD!  The service is impeccable. Everyone we met, was genuinely nice and smooth.  I'll be back for sure!

Lucked out and got seats for two around 7:30 on a Monday night! They were quoting a 2 hour wait, but as we were about to call it quits, the hostess grabbed us stating that two people had cancelled. There are only 25 seats total in the entire restaurant so it is very small. But it's very cozy and the ambiance is inviting. Even though the space is small, the décor and design is hip and modern, with staff members' family pictures and Filipino arts and crafts. Even the bathroom walls are decorated with Filipino punkzines. Pinoy punk is heard in the background.  Nick Pimentel and Genevieve Villamora of Room 11, along with chef Tom Cunanan from Ardeo + Bardeo, have created a restaurant dedicated to Filipino staples and regional food. The menu will rotate on a seasonal basis, and they've already changed their menu despite being open for a mere 3 weeks. The menu breaks down into 3 categories - Gulay (veggies and salads), Isda At Iba Pa (fish and more), and Carne (meat). My recommendation is to try something from every category. Also, order more! My boyfriend and I originally ordered 3 plates but quickly realized that these plates are fairly nouveau-sized so we asked for our menus back to order more.  +Ginisang Ampalaya {bitter melon, farm egg, preserved black beans}: $9 +Kinilaw {tuna, avocado, chilies}: $12 +Ginisang Tulya {littleneck clams, Chinese sausage, Sichuan chile}: $18 +Inihaw Na Liempo {pork belly, acharra, tamarind sauce}: $14 +Tapa {dried beef, farm egg, green salad}: $16  We started off with Kinilaw, which was essentially tuna ceviche. Wonderful starter, not too heavy and great flavor with the chilies and avocado sauce. Next came the Inihaw Na Liempo. This was a delicious pork belly dish marinated in tamarind sauce and garnished with acharra. You eat them as a wrap and the pork belly is fantastic. Then, we had the Ginisang Tulya. The clams were tasty and we devoured the rest of the sauce with our rice, of which they were not hesitant to give us more.  The Tapa is very, very good. I loved the farm egg and the mixture of flavors with the rice, salad, and dried beef. Finally, the Ginisang Ampalaya. If you're not a fan of bitter melon, this dish may be a little hard to swallow but they did a nice job of toning down the bitterness with the other ingredients. It's also a very healthy dish since bitter melon is chock full of nutrients.  Overall, great food and wonderful service. A little pricier given their small plates but very unique cuisine. Their limited space is great for dates or small groups (3-4) of friends but does not cater towards a larger group.

The newly opened Bad Saint offers DC a fresh new flavor.  Filipino food is severely lacking in the district, but Bad Saint fills this cultural void perfectly -- I honestly couldn't have asked for more.  The food at Bad Saint was excellent.  We had lumpiang, tapa, and pancit.  The lumpiang and tapa were outstanding.  The lumpiang was a crispy well portioned appetizer served with a delicious chili vinegar sauce.  The beef in the tapa was flavorful and crispy and the rice was cooked perfectly. Although I could have done without the cilantro, it was easily moved.  The pancit unfortunately came off slightly flat to me -- I wish they served it with calamansi to boost the flavor. Regardless the menu changes daily so every day offers a fresh new experience.  Be aware that Bad Saint is small and tightly packed, offering 2 wall benches that seat ~5 across and a couple booths that fit 4, you won't be having a large party eat here.  The music and service is excellent and the decor is folksy (but in a good way).  To sum it up, the overall the experience is like eating at your best friends moms house... Very homey feel good food and atmosphere.
